  <div class="grid" id="personal-projects">

    <div class="grid-item widescreen video-container">
      <video id="greeceVideo" autoplay loop playsinline style="width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: cover;">
        <source src="/work/experimental/greece.mp4" type="video/mp4">
      </video>
        <!-- Overlay -->
      <div class="overlay">
        <div class="text">
          <h2>Living under the two e's of Greece</h2>
          <p>«Ζῶντας κάτω ἀπό τά δύο λάμδα τῆς Ἑλλάδας»<br>
          A short animation that, hopefully, will develop into a short film.<br><br>
          Archive footage, music by Kyriakos Sfetsas and Manos Hadjidakis, a sound recording of my grandmother,
          an excerpt from an interview of Nobel-prize winner Odyseas Elytis and many Creative Commons photos,
          all shot in Greece.<br><br>
          What is this thing we call Greece? How to encapsulate this irregular amalgam into a work of art?<br><br>
          In the context of some kind of #semiotics of art, let's assume that the various artistic movements
          with their characteristic techniques reflect, in a way, the psyche of an era, a culture, the creator or
          the very fetishized object, that the individual art pieces belonging to that style are trying to portray.<br><br>
          Then, it seems to me that only the style of collage, especially the dadaistic one, i.e. the automatic creation,
          is capable of taming the waves of this country's rugged relief; of daring to soar its seas.<br><br>
          Ancient monuments or modern suffocating urban sprawl? Balkans or Europe? West or East? Subaltern or hegemonist?
          </p>
        </div>
        <button class="play-button" id="playBtn" aria-label="Play/Pause"></button>
        <button class="mute-button" id="muteBtn" aria-label="Mute/Unmute"></button>
